  "StepCount": 7,
  "ExecutionTrace": [
    "Step 0: Idle",
    "Step 1: Thinking\n  [{ Id = eb7f06d1-9d03-4ed6-b757-b6e36cf4a6a3\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId fd5679de-1353-4cb8-8565-1ebea28fc05e\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some (Agent (AgentId 5093eb53-d973-4aef-b946-7cd20b7267b7))\n     Performative = Request\n     Intent = Some Coding\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022### Task Summary\n\n**Goal:** Write a simple F# function that calculates the factorial of a number using recursion.\n\n**Constraints:**\n- Use recursion.\n- Handle edge cases for 0 and negative numbers.\n\n**Validation Criteria:** \n- Function returns correct factorial values.\n\n### Solution\n\nTo calculate the factorial of a number using recursion in F#, we need to define a recursive function. The factorial of a non-negative integer \\( n \\) (denoted as \\( n! \\)) is defined as:\n\\[ n! = n \\times (n-1) \\times (n-2) \\times \\ldots \\times 1 \\]\nwith the base case being:\n\\[ 0! = 1 \\]\n\nFor negative numbers, the factorial is not defined, so we should handle this edge case by returning an appropriate value or raising an error.\n\nHere\u0027s how you can implement this in F#:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nlet rec factorial n =\n    match n with\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\n    | _ when n \u003C 0 -\u003E failwith \u0022Factorial is not defined for negative numbers\u0022\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n### Explanation\n\n1. **Base Case:** When \\( n = 0 \\), the function returns 1, as \\( 0! = 1 \\).\n2. **Negative Numbers:** If \\( n \u003C 0 \\), the function raises an error because the factorial is not defined for negative numbers.\n3. **Recursive Case:** For positive integers, the function multiplies \\( n \\) by the factorial of \\( n-1 \\).\n\n### Validation\n\nTo validate this function, you can test it with various inputs:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nprintfn \u0022%d\u0022 (factorial 5)   // Expected output: 120\nprintfn \u0022%d\u0022 (factorial 0)   // Expected output: 1\ntry\n    printfn \u0022%d\u0022 (factorial -1)\nwith\n| ex -\u003E printfn \u0022Error: %s\u0022 ex.Message  // Should print an error message\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n### Final Solution\n\nThe final solution is a recursive function in F# that calculates the factorial of a number, handling edge cases for negative numbers. The code is provided above.\n\n**File Path:** \u0060src/Program.fs\u0060\u0022\n     Timestamp = 2025-12-28 9:07:09 AM\n     Metadata = map [] }]",
    "Step 2: Acting\n  ({ Name = \u0022fsharp_eval\u0022\n     Description =\n      \u0022Evaluates F# code using F# Interactive. Input JSON: { \u0022code\u0022: \u0022let x = 1 \u002B 2 in x * 3\u0022 } or { \u0022script\u0022: \u0022path/to/script.fsx\u0022 }. Returns evaluation result or error.\u0022\n     Version = \u00221.0.0\u0022\n     ParentVersion = None\n     CreatedAt = 2025-12-28 9:05:51 AM\n     Execute = \u003Cfun:resilientExecute@28\u003E\n     ThingDescription = None },\n   \u0022{\n    \u0022code\u0022: \u0022let rec factorial n =\\n    match n with\\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\\n    | _ when n \u003C 0 -\u003E failwith \\\u0022Factorial is not defined for negative numbers\\\u0022\\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\u0022\n  }\u0022)",
    "Step 3: Observing\n  ({ Name = \u0022fsharp_eval\u0022\n     Description =\n      \u0022Evaluates F# code using F# Interactive. Input JSON: { \u0022code\u0022: \u0022let x = 1 \u002B 2 in x * 3\u0022 } or { \u0022script\u0022: \u0022path/to/script.fsx\u0022 }. Returns evaluation result or error.\u0022\n     Version = \u00221.0.0\u0022\n     ParentVersion = None\n     CreatedAt = 2025-12-28 9:05:51 AM\n     Execute = \u003Cfun:resilientExecute@28\u003E\n     ThingDescription = None }, \u0022\u2705 EVAL SUCCEEDED\n\nOutput:\n\u0022)",
    "Step 4: Idle",
    "Step 5: Thinking\n  [{ Id = eb7f06d1-9d03-4ed6-b757-b6e36cf4a6a3\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId fd5679de-1353-4cb8-8565-1ebea28fc05e\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some (Agent (AgentId 5093eb53-d973-4aef-b946-7cd20b7267b7))\n     Performative = Request\n     Intent = Some Coding\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022### Task Summary\n\n**Goal:** Write a simple F# function that calculates the factorial of a number using recursion.\n\n**Constraints:**\n- Use recursion.\n- Handle edge cases for 0 and negative numbers.\n\n**Validation Criteria:** \n- Function returns correct factorial values.\n\n### Solution\n\nTo calculate the factorial of a number using recursion in F#, we need to define a recursive function. The factorial of a non-negative integer \\( n \\) (denoted as \\( n! \\)) is defined as:\n\\[ n! = n \\times (n-1) \\times (n-2) \\times \\ldots \\times 1 \\]\nwith the base case being:\n\\[ 0! = 1 \\]\n\nFor negative numbers, the factorial is not defined, so we should handle this edge case by returning an appropriate value or raising an error.\n\nHere\u0027s how you can implement this in F#:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nlet rec factorial n =\n    match n with\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\n    | _ when n \u003C 0 -\u003E failwith \u0022Factorial is not defined for negative numbers\u0022\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n### Explanation\n\n1. **Base Case:** When \\( n = 0 \\), the function returns 1, as \\( 0! = 1 \\).\n2. **Negative Numbers:** If \\( n \u003C 0 \\), the function raises an error because the factorial is not defined for negative numbers.\n3. **Recursive Case:** For positive integers, the function multiplies \\( n \\) by the factorial of \\( n-1 \\).\n\n### Validation\n\nTo validate this function, you can test it with various inputs:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nprintfn \u0022%d\u0022 (factorial 5)   // Expected output: 120\nprintfn \u0022%d\u0022 (factorial 0)   // Expected output: 1\ntry\n    printfn \u0022%d\u0022 (factorial -1)\nwith\n| ex -\u003E printfn \u0022Error: %s\u0022 ex.Message  // Should print an error message\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n### Final Solution\n\nThe final solution is a recursive function in F# that calculates the factorial of a number, handling edge cases for negative numbers. The code is provided above.\n\n**File Path:** \u0060src/Program.fs\u0060\u0022\n     Timestamp = 2025-12-28 9:07:09 AM\n     Metadata = map [] };\n   { Id = 65d22b90-af2e-4bc4-b4f8-a85a0e448e41\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId 550c2c9d-e376-4727-9a65-bc0c204f5f27\n     Sender = Agent (AgentId 5093eb53-d973-4aef-b946-7cd20b7267b7)\n     Receiver = Some System\n     Performative = Inform\n     Intent = None\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022\u0060\u0060\u0060tool\n{\n  \u0022name\u0022: \u0022fsharp_eval\u0022,\n  \u0022arguments\u0022: {\n    \u0022code\u0022: \u0022let rec factorial n =\\n    match n with\\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\\n    | _ when n \u003C 0 -\u003E failwith \\\u0022Factorial is not defined for negative numbers\\\u0022\\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\u0022\n  }\n}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\u0022\n     Timestamp = 2025-12-28 9:07:11 AM\n     Metadata = map [] };\n   { Id = 39ebe41d-155e-495c-9b6f-1b524cc702f2\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId 6228d8b0-61d8-4844-a1ab-5a417d182a6b\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some System\n     Performative = Inform\n     Intent = None\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n  